	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2076><span id=Sage>Totem</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>11337 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.74]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The atmosphere of the story is good.&nbsp;&nbsp;You are descriptive and allow the reader to get a feel for the character, even for the brief amount you have written.  The colloquilisms are a nice touch, although for your target audience they may be standard idiom.<br><br>Is this a definite work in progress?  Or is this a tentative effort to see if you want to be a writer?  Either way, you have-- as we have all seen in the Asylum --the talent to produce good writing.<br><br>If you were to take any advice from a hack such as myself, I'd recommend fleshing the scenes out, allow for an even fuller sense of what is happening, what is going on in your protagonist's mind, and add as much detail as you can short of bogging the plotline down.  Don't be in too much of a hurry to get to the next part or scene.<br><br><span class=sm>Just as an aside, what's with the homoerotic ball squeezing scene?  If this story is geared toward adventure/spy thriller readers, a lingering emphasis on the tactile sensations of another dude's sack may cause some consternation among your reader...</span class=sm><br><br>Totem</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>President of N.E.G.R.O.S., an affirmative action organization<br><br><a href=HTTP://www.zombo.com/ target=akztarg><span class=lg><span style='color: Red;'>Z</span style='color: Red;'><span style='color: Orange;'>o</span style='color: Orange;'><span style='color: Blue;'>m</span style='color: Blue;'><span style='color: Purple;'>b</span style='color: Purple;'><span style='color: Teal;'>o</span style='color: Teal;'><span style='color: Blue;'>.</span style='color: Blue;'><span style='color: Orange;'>c</span style='col