<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f1092073804177575565>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=211220&mid=1092073804177575565>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=211220&mid=1092073804177575565>Back to me roots</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=211220&mid=1092073804177575565#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Aug 9th 1:50 PM 2004</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=211220><span id=Guru>Nobby</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>2944 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.31]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>My family name being 'Mortimer', I'd heard various explanations as to how the name came about.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a linguist it was apparent that it was the bastardisation of Latin or French words for 'Dead' and 'Sea' or 'Lake'.<br><br>It's an old name, and the family has conistently maintained a reputation of being vicious immoral bastards.  Roger (1287 to 1330) held his Dad to ransom, shagged the Queen (Isabel) and had the King (Eddy II) tortured and murdered). He was effectively ruling England from 1327 to 1330 when he was Hanged at Tyburn<br>His progeny played major parts in the Wars of the Roses (allegedly changing sides from time to time).<br><br>The most plausible story which floated around the centuries about the name's origin  was that a French nobleman fought bravely on the shores of the Dead Sea during one of the various Crusades.  As was the case at the time, nobles were often given (or merely took) the name of places where they'd fought bravely. It made sense.<br><br>Until, that is, my research found that no notable battles had taken place by the Dead Sea during the 400 years of xenophobic butchery in the Middle East.<br><br>Back to the drawing Board. . . <br><br>In 2002 I was scouring a map of Normandy (looking for ther site where relatives had fought and fallen during Operation Overlord in 1944.  A small village caught my eye by the name of 'Mortemer sur Eaulne'.  Web searches drew a blank at the time, but in the Spring of 2004 I had a few days on my hands.  The boys had gone to stay with their Mom and I was able to sling a grip-bag in the back of the car and drive the 200 miles south to Calais.<br><br>I try to get to France a few times a year, and often end up in Rouen where we proud Brits wrote another black mark in our International hate list.  In 1431 we burned the 19 year old Jeanne D'Arc (La Poucelle) at the stake.  I think she was convicted of trying to overthrow our land grab there or some such.  Such a beautiful city though, and the locals seem to remember more about the liberation in 1944 than our barbarism of the 15th Century.<br><br>While in Rouen I asked a few locals about 'Mortemer'.  <br>&quot;Ahh. . the old Abbey!&quot; they said.  Having being given such an interesting lead, it would have been churlish to not drink myself under the table with them, so I obliged.  <br>The next morning I woke with a head like a Smith's Anvil but headed south to find the Abbey.<br><br>The Abbey was breathtaking in its beauty, almost matched by the delicious stewardess ~ a 20-something brunette with an accent like a purring tiger (she spoke no English. . . but I digress).  <br>In the 13th Century the King (Henry 'Beauclerc' I) of England and France (We'd grabbed most of the country for ourselves by then) gave a bunch of Cistercian Monks a bit of land.  Alas, it was a swamp (dead water = Morte Mer in the local vernacular of the time).  They drained it, built the Abbey and that's how it all started.  One of the monks left in the 14th Century and established a small settlement some 80Km (50miles) North East on the banks of the River Eaulne. This now remains as the pictureaque country village of 'Mortemer sur Eaulne'<br><br>Mostly restored in the 17th Century and largely knocked down again during the Revolution, the Abbey is now known as the most haunted Chateau in France.<br><br>I'm not so romantic to ignore the likelihood that through some long passed adoption and deceit, my lineage may be broken.  But to stand on the very site where my family name came into being was moving.<br>Hoping to go back soon and take the kids.<br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br><span class=sm><i>"You must be old or rich, Nob.&nbsp;&nbsp;No one's latin is that good who was born after 1975." - Smash</i></span class=sm><br><br><span class=sm>Those are my principles and if you don't like them. . . well, I have others.<br>Groucho Marx</span class=sm><br><br><i>When waving at a Police Officer, it is important to use all the fingers on your hand </i></td></tr>
